\frametitle{Tridiagonal Matrices}

\begin{equation*}
\left[\begin{array}{@{}rrrr@{}}
2 & -1 & 0 & 0\\
-1 & 2 & -1 & 0\\
0 & -1 & 2 & -1\\
0 & 0 & -1 & 2
\end{array}\right].
\end{equation*}

The diagonal elements need not be equal.  The general
form of a tridiagonal matrix is
\begin{equation*}
    A = \begin{bmatrix}
    a_1 & b_1 & & & & &\\
    c_2 & a_2 & b_2& & & &\\
    & c_3 & a_3 & b_3& & &\\
    & & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots& &\\
    \\
    & & & & c_{n-1}& a_{n-1}& b_{n-1}\\
    & & & & & c_n & a_n
    \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}




